These are the solutions to the problem from other agents:

 One agent solution: ```First, let's consider the regular octahedron. An octahedron has 6 vertices, with each vertex connected to 4 other vertices by edges. This creates 8 equilateral triangles, each with a vertex at the center of the octahedron.

Next, we note that the distances from point P to 5 out of the 6 vertices are given. Since P is not on the octahedron, P lies inside the octahedron. This means that the shortest distance from P to any of the vertices is along the line segment connecting P to that vertex.

If we think about the geometry of the octahedron, it's clear that the shortest distance from P to the remaining vertex will be along the same line segment that connects P to the vertex. This is because, if we imagine drawing a line from P to the center of the octahedron (the midpoint of the line segment connecting that vertex to the vertex on the opposite side), the distance from P to that midpoint will be shorter than the distance from P to the remaining vertex.

Therefore, the distance from P to the sixth vertex is the same as the distance from P to the fifth vertex, which is 11. 

Thus, the distance from P to the sixth vertex is \boxed{11}.```

